<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How do I scale a recipe up or down?", answer: "Divide the desired number of servings by the original number of servings to get a multiplier. Multiply each ingredient amount by this multiplier. For example, to double a recipe that serves 4 to serve 8, multiply every ingredient by 2." },
  { question: "Do all ingredients scale linearly?", answer: "Most ingredients scale linearly, but seasonings, salt, leavening agents (baking powder, baking soda, yeast), and spices often need less than a linear increase when scaling up. Start with 1.5x for these when doubling a recipe." },
  { question: "Can I halve a recipe that calls for one egg?", answer: "Yes. Beat the egg, measure it (about 3 tablespoons), and use half (1.5 tablespoons). Alternatively, use a small egg or egg substitute for the halved amount." },
  { question: "Does scaling a recipe affect cooking time?", answer: "Scaling ingredients does not always change cooking time proportionally. Larger volumes may need slightly longer cooking, while individual portion sizes (like cookies) remain the same. Use an instant-read thermometer to verify doneness." },
  { question: "How do I scale baking recipes accurately?", answer: "Use weight measurements (grams) instead of volume (cups) for the most accurate scaling. Weigh each ingredient and multiply by your scaling factor. This eliminates measuring cup inconsistencies." }
]) %>

