    <%= render "shared/calculator_rating", slug: "recipe-scaler" %>
    <div class="mb-8"><%= render "shared/ad_slot", slot: "in_results" %></div>

    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <h2>How to Use the Recipe Scaler</h2>
      <p>
        Our free recipe scaler makes it simple to adjust any recipe for a different number of servings. Enter the original number of servings the recipe makes, type in how many servings you want, then add each ingredient with its amount and unit. The calculator instantly computes the scaled amounts using a precise multiplier so you never have to do the math yourself.
      </p>
      <p>
        Whether you are cooking for a crowd, halving a recipe for a weeknight dinner for two, or tripling a batch of cookies for a bake sale, the recipe scaler handles the arithmetic. It works with any unit of measurement, including cups, tablespoons, grams, ounces, and milliliters.
      </p>

      <div class="my-6"><%= render "shared/ad_slot", slot: "in_content" %></div>

      <h2>Tips for Scaling Recipes Accurately</h2>
      <p>
        While most ingredients scale linearly, a few categories behave differently when you multiply or divide a recipe. Seasonings, salt, and spices are best adjusted conservatively. When doubling a recipe, start with 1.5 times the original seasoning amount, taste, and adjust. Leavening agents like baking powder and baking soda also should not be scaled in perfect proportion for very large multiples because carbon dioxide production does not increase linearly with quantity.
      </p>

      <h3>Cooking and Baking Adjustments</h3>
      <p>
        Scaling a recipe changes the total volume of food but not necessarily the cooking time or temperature. A doubled cake batter in the same size pan will need more time in the oven, while the same batter split into two pans will bake in roughly the original time. Always use a thermometer or visual cues to judge doneness rather than relying solely on the timer.
      </p>

      <h3>Weight vs. Volume Measurements</h3>
      <p>
        For the most accurate results, especially in baking, use weight measurements (grams or ounces) rather than volume (cups, tablespoons). A cup of flour can vary by 30 grams or more depending on how it is scooped. Weighing eliminates that variability and makes scaling simple multiplication.
      </p>

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <h3>How do I scale a recipe up or down?</h3>
      <p>Divide the desired number of servings by the original number of servings to get a multiplier. Multiply each ingredient amount by this multiplier. For example, to double a recipe that serves 4 to serve 8, multiply every ingredient by 2.</p>

      <h3>Do all ingredients scale linearly?</h3>
      <p>Most ingredients scale linearly, but seasonings, salt, leavening agents (baking powder, baking soda, yeast), and spices often need less than a linear increase when scaling up. Start with 1.5x for these when doubling a recipe.</p>

      <h3>Can I halve a recipe that calls for one egg?</h3>
      <p>Yes. Beat the egg, measure it (about 3 tablespoons), and use half (1.5 tablespoons). Alternatively, use a small egg or egg substitute for the halved amount.</p>

      <h3>Does scaling a recipe affect cooking time?</h3>
      <p>Scaling ingredients does not always change cooking time proportionally. Larger volumes may need slightly longer cooking, while individual portion sizes (like cookies) remain the same. Use an instant-read thermometer to verify doneness.</p>

      <h3>How do I scale baking recipes accurately?</h3>
      <p>Use weight measurements (grams) instead of volume (cups) for the most accurate scaling. Weigh each ingredient and multiply by your scaling factor. This eliminates measuring cup inconsistencies.</p>
    </article>

